[normal]1.
[normal]4
[normal] 
[normal]Based on examination of a small sample of crime and incident records in each of the 43 Home Office-funded forces, 
[normal]HMIC
[normal] 
[normal]found
[normal] 
[normal]that the majority of forces 
[normal]were correctly
[normal] recording crimes based on the information available within an incident record
[normal]. However,
[normal] 
[normal]this conclusion mask
[normal]ed
[normal] 
[normal]a 
[normal]wide variation 
[normal]in 
[normal]the 
[normal]accuracy 
[normal]of force decisions in this regard
[normal]: 
[normal]18 forces correctly recorded crime
[normal]s in 95% or more of cases; 15 forces did so in between 90 and 94% 
[normal]of 
[normal]cases; and 11 forces in between 86 and 89% of cases.
[normal] 
[normal]This
[normal] 
[normal]could mean 
[normal]forces that made poorer decisions 
[normal]were unde
[normal]r-recording some crimes, which c
[normal]ould have 
[normal]a corresponding impact 
[normal]on the ac
[normal]curacy of published crime statistics
[normal] (although 
[normal]it should be noted that 
[normal]the size of the sample used in this inspection was too small to make any definite statements on this – it was used instead as an indicator of where there might be issues)
[normal].  
