[normal]The Crime Scene [bold](2012)[bold]2.
[normal]2
[normal] 
[normal]The 2012 HMIC report
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]The Crime Scene
[normal] – 
[normal]A review of police crime and incident reports
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]found
[normal] 
[normal]that forces which 
[normal]demonstrate
[normal]d
[normal] good standards of data quality all 
[normal]had
[normal] 
[normal]a clearly identified 
[normal]chief officer
[normal] lead who act
[normal]ed 
[normal]as the force champion for such issues
[normal],
[normal] and 
[normal]who 
[normal]actively promote
[normal]d
[normal] good crime and incident re
[normal]cording standards. 
[normal]HMIC found that t
[normal]he message 
[normal]such chief offic
[normal]ers
[normal] 
[normal]sen
[normal]t
[normal] to their force
[normal]s
[normal] about the importance of maintaining high standards 
[normal]in this regard 
[normal]need
[normal]ed
[normal] to be consistent, unequivocal
[normal],
[normal] and 
[normal]practi
[normal]s
[normal]ed
[normal]. It 
[normal]also needed to be
[normal] clearly understood by staff.
[normal] 
[normal]2.3 
[normal]Other
[normal] aspects 
[normal]which HMIC reported as being the most 
[normal]influential in maintaining standards in recording crime were: good governance and supervision; and knowledgeable staff – in particular, an objective force crime registrar with strong influence over local crime recording decisions, to ensure these were not 
[normal]unduly influenced by the pressure to achieve certain outcomes.
[normal] We concluded that: “The final responsibility for HOCR compliance should not, therefore, be vested in the same individuals as are accountable for crime reduction and detection” (para 5.6).
[normal]Forg[bold]ing the Links – Rape investigation and prosecution (2012)[bold]2.4 In this report (which was conducted jointly with HM Inspectorate of the Crown Prosecution Service), HMIC found that there were wide variations across forces in the number of rapes that remained on the system (and so were investigated) compared to those
[normal] that were ‘no crimed’ (i.e. removed from the crime recording system because the police decide that a crime has not been committed). We 
[normal]stated
[normal] that 
[normal]“
[normal]i
[normal]n the past performance pressures may have influenced forces
[normal]’
[normal] approaches to either the initial recording or
[normal] subsequent levels 
[normal]of ‘no crimes’ for rape offending” (para 1.29), and advocated instead a regime that places equal emphasis on
[normal] 
[normal]an analysis of rape crimes and associated intelligence
[normal] as on low offending levels
[normal], 
[normal]which would act
[normal] as an encouragement to retain
[normal] crime records on the system.
[normal] 
[normal]HMIC’s 2013/14 crime data integrity programme[bold]2.5 Our programme for 2013/14 will 
[normal]consider
[normal] more widely the influences that may result in the mis-recording of crime.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.1 
[normal]HMIC 
[normal]considers
[normal] 
[normal]the 
[normal]role of the 
[normal]f
[normal]orce 
[normal]c
[normal]rime 
[normal]r
[normal]egistrar 
[normal](FCR) 
[normal]to be
[normal] 
[normal]central to ensuring 
[normal]force systems for recording crime 
[normal]are 
[normal]effective and accurate
[normal]. 
[normal]This role is a requirement detailed in the 
[normal]National Crime Recording Standard (NCRS)
[normal],
[normal] which states
[normal] (in section 4.2)
[normal]:
[normal]To ensure the NCRS is maintained within the force, and to provide greater consistency within and across forces, each force should appoint an FCR to act as final arbiter for the audit process; the interpretation of the counting rules; and for ensuring the o
[normal]utcome from investigations into those crimes is correctly recorded. The FCR must be outside operational line command and answerable to the chief officer with overall responsibility for the accuracy and integrity of crime recording processes. To ensure that
[normal] the responsibilities of the post are effectively met, a deputy or other identified person should be appointed. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The 
[normal]key
[normal] tasks of an FCR are: 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]There is full recognition
[normal] 
[normal]that the FCR role and responsibilities continue to evolve over time.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Crime Scene [bold](2012)[bold]3.
[normal]2
[normal] Our 2012 
[normal]review found forces that finalised incidents well ha
[normal]d
[normal] a strong FCR, who act
[normal]ed
[normal] as the final arbiter for disputes 
[normal]in respect of 
[normal]the interpretation of the counting rules and enjoy
[normal]ed
[normal] clear, unequivocal chief officer support. Indeed, evidence from the review indicated that 34 of the 44 forces reviewed claimed to
[normal] have sufficiently strong, independent FCRs, with clear chief officer support.
[normal] 
[normal]However, 
[normal]HMIC 
[normal]found limited evidence of forces directly assessing whether their own crime quality audits provided confidence that their crime figures gave an accurate account o
[normal]f their 
[normal]performance
[normal],
[normal] and
[normal] f
[normal]ew forces compare crime audits with crime performance in any meaningful way
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.
[normal]3
[normal] 
[normal]I
[normal]n 2012
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]HMIC also reported 
[normal]that 
[normal]evidence strongly supports the notion that leadership, supervision and oversight help attain good crime and incident data quality. Strong and effective leadership is therefore a critical component in raising standards. 
[normal]Equally, where there is the slightest
[normal] doubt as to the chief officer’s expectation 
[normal]in relation to
[normal] crime and incident data quality, standards will inevitably slip.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]4.1 HMIC recognises that there is still mor
[normal]e to be done to secure the integrity of 
[normal]police
[normal]-
[normal]recorded crime data
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]T
[normal]he work of the Crime Statistics Advisory Committee (CSAC)
[normal],
[normal] as an independent advisor on matters related to the measurement of crime
[normal],
[normal] and the collection and presentation of crime data
[normal],
[normal] is welcomed.
[normal] The rest of this answer focuses on what HMIC has done (and is doing) to ensure the integrity of this data. 
[normal]4.2 
[normal]Crime data and crime recording are 
[normal]complex areas of policing,
[normal] and there continues to be a need for greater clarity and understandi
[normal]ng. Therefore, 
[normal]HMIC has 
[normal]inspected police crime data integrity for a number of years
[normal]. 
[normal]This has included inspections dedicated
[normal] specifically
[normal] 
[normal]to crime data
[normal],
[normal] as well as integrating consideration of crime data accuracy within other formal inspection activity
[normal], su
[normal]ch as HMIC inspections of the approach taken by police forces to deal
[normal]ing
[normal] with anti-social behaviour
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]HMIC’s 2013/14[bold] crime data integrity programme[bold]4.3 
[normal]HMIC 
[normal]has
[normal] 
[normal]committed to inspect
[normal]ing
[normal] crime data integrity 
[normal]again 
[normal]during 2013/14. Her Majesty’s Chief 
[normal]Inspector of Constabulary confirmed this commitment to the Home Affairs Select Committee
[normal] in May 2013
[normal],
[normal] and agreed to report on the issue in 
[normal]autumn
[normal] 2014. 
[normal]4.
[normal]4
[normal] This inspection will include 
[normal]our
[normal] assessment of the accuracy of crime recording through the various routes that crimes can be reported to the police
[normal] 
[normal](
[normal]such as through calls to control rooms, referrals to specialist 
[normal]investigation
[normal] departments from other public bodies or directly to officers
[normal])
[normal]. Our initial findings will be 
[normal]provid
[normal]ed 
[normal]in an interim report 
[normal](as
[normal] requested by the Home Secretary
