[normal]4.
[normal]6
[normal] The specific objectives of the inspection involve establishing:
[normal]Monitoring of force performance[bold]4.
[normal]7
[normal] In addition to the formal crime data integrity programme
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]Her Majesty’s Inspectors of Constabulary (HMIs) routinely monitor the performance of police forces
[normal], including 
[normal]as regards
[normal] 
[normal]the integrity of data
[normal].
[normal] This 
[normal]helps to 
[normal]ensure that:
[normal]•    
[normal]emerging problems 
[normal]with the efficiency or effectiveness of individual forces are spotted quickly, and Chief Constables and local policing bodies
[normal] 
[normal]are aware of those problems and are taking corrective action; and
[normal]•    
[normal]if problems with the efficiency or effectiveness of a forc
[normal]e are enduring and there is a low prospect of 
[normal]their
[normal] 
[normal]being resolved, those problems are raised formally with the local policing body, so that they can respond.
[normal]4.
[normal]8
[normal] Routine monitoring identifies 
[normal]potential
[normal] 
[normal]issues for closer scrutiny. Some of these will be out
[normal]side the control of the force and local policing body, or will already have been tackled; but some may be indicators of systemic or management failings in the force. The decision 
[normal]as to
[normal] 
[normal]whether to follow up with the force and local policing body over any co
[normal]ncerns rests with the HMI who leads on HMIC’s relationship with that force area. 
