[normal]The 
[normal]Crime Scene – 
[normal]A review of police crime and incident reports,
[normal] HMIC, London, January 2012, para 2.4.
[normal] When a crime has been recorded, it can only be declassified (which is referred to as ‘no-crimed’) if the strict criteria set out in the HOCR apply. No-crimes account for approximately 3-4% of overall recorded crime. No-criming is an important part of the 
[normal]HOCR as it caters for situations where the original decision to record a crime clearly turns out to be wrong (for example, where someone reports to the police that their car has been stolen from a multi-storey car park, only to find it later on a different
[normal] floor). While it is appropriate for some cases to be no-crimed, when this is done incorrectly it can mean that suspects may not be brought to justice and the force’s published crime figures will be inaccurate.
